        "user": "How does \"transformer (architecture)\" differ from CNN (Convolutional Neural Network)?",
        "assistant": "A **Transformer** differs from a **CNN (Convolutional Neural Network)** mainly in how it combines information across positions.\n\n| Aspect | Transformer | CNN |\n|---|---|---|\n| Core mechanism | Multi-head self-attention | Convolutional filters/kernels |\n| Information mixing | Each position can attend to many or all other positions directly | Each layer usually sees a local neighborhood |\n| Receptive field | Potentially global in one attention layer | Grows with depth, kernel size, dilation, or pooling |\n| Relationship modeling | Dynamic: attention weights depend on the input | Mostly fixed learned filters applied across positions |\n| Position/order handling | Needs positional encodings or embeddings | Spatial/sequence locality is built into convolution |\n| Parallelism | Processes positions in parallel | Also processes positions in parallel |\n| Common strengths | Long-range dependencies, flexible token interactions, language modeling | Local pattern detection, images, audio, efficient feature extraction |\n| Typical examples | GPT, BERT, T5, LLaMA | ResNet, VGG, U-Net, ConvNets for vision/audio |\n\nA **CNN** applies learned filters over local regions. For example, in an image, early convolution layers may detect edges or textures; deeper layers combine those into shapes and objects.\n\nA **Transformer**, by contrast, uses **self-attention**, allowing one token or image patch to directly weigh its relationship to other tokens or patches.\n\nIn short:\n\n> A CNN learns local patterns using convolutional filters, while a Transformer learns relationships between positions using self-attention.\n\nOne important nuance: both CNNs and Transformers can process positions in parallel. The big difference is that CNNs use **local, shared convolution kernels**, whereas Transformers use **global or broad attention-based interactions**.",
