        "user": "How does \"transformer (architecture)\" differ from MoE (Mixture of Experts)?",
        "assistant": "A **Transformer** and an **MoE (Mixture of Experts)** differ because they refer to different architectural ideas.\n\nA **Transformer** is a full neural network architecture for sequence processing, built from:\n\n- multi-head self-attention\n- position-wise feed-forward layers\n- residual connections\n- layer normalization\n- parallel processing of sequence positions\n\nAn **MoE** is a technique for scaling part of a neural network by replacing some dense layers with multiple “expert” subnetworks, where a routing mechanism chooses which experts handle each input.\n\n| Aspect | Transformer | MoE |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | A sequence-modeling architecture | A sparsely activated expert-routing mechanism |\n| Core mechanism | Self-attention + feed-forward layers | Router/gating network selects experts |\n| Main purpose | Model relationships among sequence positions | Increase model capacity efficiently |\n| Processing style | All tokens pass through the same dense layers in a standard Transformer | Different tokens may be sent to different experts |\n| Common location | Whole architecture | Usually inserted inside Transformer feed-forward layers |\n| Example models | BERT, GPT, T5, LLaMA | Switch Transformer, Mixtral, GShard-style models |\n\nA standard Transformer layer might look like:\n\n```text\nself-attention\n→ feed-forward network\n```\n\nA Transformer with MoE may replace the feed-forward network with expert routing:\n\n```text\nself-attention\n→ router\n→ selected expert feed-forward networks\n```\n\nSo the two are not mutually exclusive. Many MoE models are still **Transformers**.\n\nFor example:\n\n> **Mixtral** is a Transformer-based model that uses Mixture-of-Experts feed-forward layers.\n\nIn short:\n\n> A Transformer is the overall attention-based architecture; MoE is a scaling method that can be added inside a Transformer, usually by replacing dense feed-forward layers with routed expert networks.",
